5. Module Description

5.1 Backend modules

- `src/index.js`
  - Purpose: Configure middleware, set up routes, connect to MongoDB, start server. Exposes `/health`.

- Routers (`src/routes`)
  - `employees.js`: `/api/employees` CRUD
  - `level1.js` .. `level7.js`: `/api/level{n}` CRUD for each OKR level
  - `performance.js`: `/api/performance` endpoints

- Controllers (`src/controllers`)
  - Responsibility: validate inputs, call models, shape responses, handle errors. Implemented per resource (employeeController, levelXController, performanceController).

- Models (`src/models`)
  - `employee.js`: Employee schema with `pre('validate')` hook to auto-assign `empCode`.
  - `level1Okr.js` .. `level7Okr.js`: Per-level OKR schemas with fields for KRs and quarterly progress; `pre('save')` hooks auto-generate per-level codes using `Counter`.
  - `counter.js`: sequence store used by models to increment codes.

5.2 Frontend modules

- `src/lib/api.js`
  - Central API client. Default `baseUrl` uses `VITE_API_URL` or `https://okr-system-backend.onrender.com` hardcoded fallback.
  - Exposes functions: `listEmployees`, `getEmployee`, `createEmployee`, `updateEmployee`, `deleteEmployee`, list/create/update for level OKRs, `getEmployeeOKRs`, `getOKRHierarchy`.

- Pages and Components
  - Pages: Employee master, OKR workspaces (Level 1..7), OKR performance.
  - Components: LabeledInput, KeyResultInput, QuarterInput, Toasts, NavBar, etc.

6. Database Design (full)

6.1 Collections and fields (complete listing)

Employees collection (`employees`)
- `_id` : ObjectId (generated by MongoDB)
- `empCode` : Number (unique, application primary key; auto-generated by `Counter` if omitted)
- `empName` : String (max 40)
- `empDesignation` : String (max 40)
- `empLevel` : Number
- `createdAt`, `updatedAt` : Date (timestamps)

Level1OKR collection (`level1okrs`)
- `_id` : ObjectId
- `empLevel` : Number (default 1)
- `level1OkrCode` : Number (unique, indexed)
- `empCode` : Number (required)
- `empName` : String (max 40)
- `okrDate` : Date
- `okrDesc` : String (max 100)
- `kr1`..`kr5` : String (each max 100)
- `q1_percentage`..`q4_percentage` : Number (0..100)
- `q1_comment`..`q4_comment` : String (max 100)
- `createdAt`, `updatedAt` : Date

Level2OKR (`level2okrs`)
- `_id`, `level1OkrCode` (Number, required, index), `level2OkrCode` (unique), `empLevel` (2), `empCode`, `empName`, `okrDate`, `okrDesc`, `kr1`..`kr5`, `q1_percentage`..`q4_percentage`, `q1_comment`..`q4_comment`, timestamps.

Level3OKR .. Level7OKR follow the same pattern:
- Each includes a reference code to its parent level (e.g., `level3` includes `level2OkrCode`), a unique level-specific code (e.g., `level3OkrCode`), `empLevel`, `empCode`, `empName`, KRs, quarterly percentages and comments, timestamps.

Counters collection (`counters`)
- `_id` : String (identifier for sequence, e.g., `employee`, `level1okr`)
- `seq` : Number (current sequence)

6.2 ER diagram (comprehensive)

```mermaid
erDiagram
    EMPLOYEE {
      ObjectId _id
      Number empCode PK
      String empName
      String empDesignation
      Number empLevel
    }
    LEVEL1OKR {
      ObjectId _id
      Number level1OkrCode PK
      Number empCode FK
      String okrDesc
      String kr1
      String kr2
      String kr3
      String kr4
      String kr5
    }
    LEVEL2OKR {
      ObjectId _id
      Number level2OkrCode PK
      Number level1OkrCode FK
      Number empCode FK
    }
    EMPLOYEE ||--o{ LEVEL1OKR : "owns"
    LEVEL1OKR ||--o{ LEVEL2OKR : "parent_of"
    LEVEL2OKR ||--o{ LEVEL3OKR : "parent_of"
    LEVEL3OKR ||--o{ LEVEL4OKR : "parent_of"
    LEVEL4OKR ||--o{ LEVEL5OKR : "parent_of"
    LEVEL5OKR ||--o{ LEVEL6OKR : "parent_of"
    LEVEL6OKR ||--o{ LEVEL7OKR : "parent_of"
```

6.3 Indexes and constraints
- Unique indexes on per-level code fields (`level{n}OkrCode`) and `empCode` index for Employee. Counters collection uses `_id` as key.
- All referential links are application-level (no DB-enforced foreign keys).

7. Build Instructions

Prerequisites
- Node.js v18+ and npm
- MongoDB instance (connection string in `MONGODB_URI`)
- For packaging: Windows build environment for electron-builder (if building Windows target)

Local Backend (development)

```powershell
cd okr_backend
npm install
# run with auto-reload
npm run dev
```

Local Frontend + Electron (development)

```powershell
cd okr_frontend
npm install
npm run dev
```

Production build (frontend web assets)

```powershell
cd okr_frontend
npm run build
```

Package desktop app (Windows)

```powershell
cd okr_frontend
npm run build:exe
```

8. Deployment

8.1 Backend — Render (recommended)

Steps
1. Connect the Git repository to Render and create a Web Service (Node).
2. Set the service Root (repository root or `okr_backend`).
3. Set Build command: `npm ci` and Start command: `npm start`.
4. Provide environment variables in Render dashboard:
   - `MONGODB_URI` (required)
   - `PORT` (optional)
   - `CLIENT_ORIGIN` (optional)

Sample `render.yaml` (place at repo root or `okr_backend` folder):

```yaml
services:
  - type: web
    name: okr-backend
    env: node
    plan: starter
    buildCommand: npm ci
    startCommand: npm start
    root: okr_backend
    envVars:
      - key: MONGODB_URI
        sync: true
```

Notes
- Render will run your build and start commands and expose the service URL; update `VITE_API_URL` in the frontend build or set `CLIENT_ORIGIN` appropriately.

8.2 Frontend packaging and distribution
- Electron-builder configured in `okr_frontend/package.json` build block.
- Running `npm run build:exe` produces Windows installer(s) and artifacts under `okr_frontend/dist_electron`.

8.3 Environment and secrets
- Use Render's environment variable management (secrets) for `MONGODB_URI` and other credentials. Never store secrets in the repo.

9. API Documentation (detailed)

Base URL
- Production (observed default): `https://okr-system-backend.onrender.com` (overridable with `VITE_API_URL`)
- Local: `http://localhost:5000` (default `PORT` 5000)

Common response envelope
- Successful responses typically return `{ data: ... }`.
- Errors return `{ error: "message" }` with appropriate HTTP status codes.

9.1 Employees

GET /api/employees
- Description: List employees (most recent first, limited to 200)
- Query: none
- Response: 200 `{ data: [ { _id, empCode, empName, empDesignation, empLevel, createdAt, updatedAt } ] }`

GET /api/employees/:id
- Description: Get employee by MongoDB ObjectId or `empCode` integer.
- Response: 200 `{ data: { ... } }` or 404

POST /api/employees
- Description: Create employee. If `empCode` omitted, auto-generated.
- Body (JSON):
  {
    "empName": "Alice",
    "empDesignation": "Engineer",
    "empLevel": 2
  }
- Response: 201 `{ data: { _id, empCode, empName, empDesignation, empLevel, createdAt } }`

PUT /api/employees/:id
- Description: Update employee by _id or empCode
- Body: Partial employee fields
- Response: 200 `{ data: { ...updated document... } }` or 404

DELETE /api/employees/:id
- Description: Delete employee by _id or empCode
- Response: 200 `{ data: { ...deleted document... } }` or 404

9.2 Level OKRs (example: Level1)

GET /api/level1
- List level 1 OKRs (recent first, limit 200)

GET /api/level1/:id
- Get by ObjectId or `level1OkrCode`

POST /api/level1
- Body (JSON): sample
  {
    "empCode": 101,
    "empName": "Alice",
    "okrDesc": "Improve platform stability",
    "kr1": "Reduce errors by 20%",
    "q1_percentage": 40
  }

PUT /api/level1/:id
- Update fields; runValidators true

DELETE /api/level1/:id

Note: Level2..Level7 endpoints mirror Level1 structure; Level2 requires `level1OkrCode` in payload, Level3 requires `level2OkrCode`, etc.

9.3 Performance

GET /api/performance/okrs/:empCode
- Description: Fetch all OKRs across levels for a given employee code.
- Response: `{ data: [ { ...okr with level info... } ] }`

GET /api/performance/:level/:okrCode
- Description: Return hierarchical OKR tree for the specified level and code. Traverses parents/children as implemented in `performanceController`.

9.4 Health

GET /health
- Returns `{ status: 'ok', timestamp: '...' }` when service is healthy.

9.5 Error codes summary
- 200 OK — success
- 201 Created — resource created
- 400 Bad Request — validation errors
- 404 Not Found — resource not found
- 500 Internal Server Error — server failure

9.6 API examples (cURL)

Create employee

```bash
curl -X POST https://okr-system-backend.onrender.com/api/employees \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"empName":"Alice","empDesignation":"Engineer","empLevel":2}'
```

Get employee OKRs (performance)

```bash
curl https://okr-system-backend.onrender.com/api/performance/okrs/101
```

10. Operational recommendations

- Add authentication & authorization for production APIs (JWT/OAuth).
- Introduce structured logging and error-tracking.
- Add automated tests and a CI pipeline that runs linters and tests on push/PR.
- Add backup plan for MongoDB and health checks for services.

